<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1478,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Levinsen, 1878" authorityName="Levinsen" authorityYear="1878" box="[273,580,1478,1503]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Bradophilidae" genus="Bradophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[273,401,1478,1503]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Bradophila</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Levinsen, G. M. R." box="[408,580,1478,1503]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="351 - 380" refId="ref47405" refString="Levinsen, G. M. R. (1878) Om nogle parasitiske Krebsdyr, der snylte hos Annelider. Fidenskalbelige Meddelelser fra dansk Naturhistorisk Forening I KJObenhavn, 1877 - 78, 351 - 380, pl. 6." type="journal article" year="1878">Levinsen, 1878</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Levinsen, G. M. R." box="[902,1086,1478,1503]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="351 - 380" refId="ref47405" refString="Levinsen, G. M. R. (1878) Om nogle parasitiske Krebsdyr, der snylte hos Annelider. Fidenskalbelige Meddelelser fra dansk Naturhistorisk Forening I KJObenhavn, 1877 - 78, 351 - 380, pl. 6." type="journal article" year="1878">Levinsen (1878)</bibRefCitation>
but over 120 years later, it was 
<bibRefCitation author="Marchenkov, A. V." box="[151,375,1514,1539]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refId="ref47852" refString="Marchenkov, A. V. (1999) Symbiotic and parasitic Crustacea off benthic marine invertebrates from the Arctic Seas of Russia. Unpublished PhD thesis, Zoological Institute, Russian Academy of Sciences, Saint Petersburg, 193 pp." type="book" year="1999">Marchenkov (1999)</bibRefCitation>
who first suggested that it belonged in a separate family and later he formally established the family (
<bibRefCitation author="Marchenkov, A. V." box="[240,453,1550,1575]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="514 - 516" refId="ref47894" refString="Marchenkov, A. V. (2002) Bradophilidae fam. nov. - the new family of mesoparasitic copepod collected from the polychaete Brada villosa from the White Sea. Parazitologiya, 36 (6), 514 - 516." type="journal article" year="2002">Marchenkov 2002</bibRefCitation>
). The genus and family have remained monotypic until recently, although 
<bibRefCitation author="Boxshall, G. A. &amp; Halsey, S. H." pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refId="ref45773" refString="Boxshall, G. A. &amp; Halsey, S. H. (2004) An Introduction to Copepod Diversity. The Ray Society, London, 966 pp." type="book" year="2004">Boxshall &amp; Halsey (2004)</bibRefCitation>
suggested a possible relationship with the poorly known 
<taxonomicName authority="M'Intosh, 1885" authorityName="M'Intosh" authorityYear="1885" box="[994,1432,1586,1611]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Bradophilidae" genus="Trophonophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bradii">
<emphasis box="[994,1240,1586,1611]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Trophonophila bradii</emphasis>
M’Intosh, 1885
</taxonomicName>
, which also occurs on a flabelligerid polychaete host, taken in deep water to the south of 
<collectingCountry box="[1134,1237,1622,1647]" name="Australia" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Australia</collectingCountry>
(M’Intosh 1885). 
<bibRefCitation author="Huys, R." box="[151,296,1658,1683]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="355 - 385" refId="ref47088" refString="Huys, R. (2016) Enigmas from the past: M'Intosh's (1885) annelidicolous copepods from the voyage of H. M. S. Challenger. Zootaxa, 4174 (1), 355 - 385. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4174.1.22" type="journal article" year="2016">Huys (2016)</bibRefCitation>
re-examined the 
<typeStatus box="[505,603,1658,1683]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">holotype</typeStatus>
female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="M'Intosh" authorityYear="1885" box="[737,837,1658,1683]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Bradophilidae" genus="Trophonophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bradii">
<emphasis box="[737,837,1658,1683]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">T. bradii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and confirmed that this genus is a member of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marchenkov" authorityYear="2002" box="[151,314,1694,1719]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Bradophilidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Bradophilidae</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Huys, R." box="[329,475,1694,1719]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="355 - 385" refId="ref47088" refString="Huys, R. (2016) Enigmas from the past: M'Intosh's (1885) annelidicolous copepods from the voyage of H. M. S. Challenger. Zootaxa, 4174 (1), 355 - 385. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4174.1.22" type="journal article" year="2016">Huys (2016)</bibRefCitation>
also considered that the name of the species should be changed to 
<taxonomicName box="[1294,1400,1694,1719]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Bradophilidae" genus="Trophonophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bradyi">
<emphasis box="[1294,1400,1694,1719]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">T. bradyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as M’Intosh (1885) explicitly named the species after George Stewardson Brady. However, since the original spelling given by M’Intosh (
<taxonomicName authorityName="M'Intosh" authorityYear="1885" box="[376,444,1766,1791]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Bradophilidae" genus="Trophonophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bradii">
<emphasis box="[376,444,1766,1791]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">bradii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) clearly constitutes an attempt at the latinization of Brady’s name, we retain the original spelling in accord with ICZN Art. 32.5.1, which states that incorrect latinization is not to be considered an inadvertent error.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1478,2007]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The globular and limbless ectosoma of adult female 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Levinsen" authorityYear="1878" box="[828,956,1874,1899]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Bradophilidae" genus="Bradophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[828,956,1874,1899]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Bradophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles that of females of the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hansen" authorityYear="1892" box="[151,322,1910,1935]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Herpyllobiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Herpyllobiidae</taxonomicName>
, but these two families differ markedly in the structure of the males: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Levinsen" authorityYear="1878" box="[1108,1235,1910,1935]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Bradophilidae" genus="Bradophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1108,1235,1910,1935]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Bradophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males have welldeveloped, prehensile antennae which are used to attach to the ectosoma of the female, plus recognizable antennules, mandibles, maxillules, maxillae, and maxillipeds (
<bibRefCitation author="Marchenkov, A. V." box="[865,1077,1982,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="514 - 516" refId="ref47894" refString="Marchenkov, A. V. (2002) Bradophilidae fam. nov. - the new family of mesoparasitic copepod collected from the polychaete Brada villosa from the White Sea. Parazitologiya, 36 (6), 514 - 516." type="journal article" year="2002">Marchenkov 2002</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Huys, R." box="[1092,1222,1982,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="355 - 385" refId="ref47088" refString="Huys, R. (2016) Enigmas from the past: M'Intosh's (1885) annelidicolous copepods from the voyage of H. M. S. Challenger. Zootaxa, 4174 (1), 355 - 385. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4174.1.22" type="journal article" year="2016">Huys 2016</bibRefCitation>
). In contrast, male herpyllobiids lack all cephalothoracic appendages except for males of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lopez-Gonzalez, Bresciani &amp; Conradi, 2006" authorityName="Lopez-Gonzalez, Bresciani &amp; Conradi" authorityYear="2006" class="Maxillopoda" family="Herpyllobiidae" genus="Gottoniella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[960,1088,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Gottoniella</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lopez-Gonzalez, P. J. &amp; Bresciani, J. &amp; Conradi, M." pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="243 - 259" refId="ref47580" refString="Lopez-Gonzalez, P. J., Bresciani, J. &amp; Conradi, M. (2006) New genus, three new species and new records of Herpyllobiidae Hansen, 1892 (Crustacea, Copepoda), parasites of polychaetes from Antarctica. Scientia Marina, 70, 243 - 259. https: // doi. org / 10.3989 / scimar. 2006.70 n 2243." type="journal article" year="2006">López-González, Bresciani &amp; Conradi, 2006</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, which possess a pair of 3-segmented subchelate limbs, identified as probably the maxillipeds by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lopez-Gonzalez, P. J. &amp; Bresciani, J. &amp; Conradi, M." box="[151,483,223,248]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="243 - 259" refId="ref47580" refString="Lopez-Gonzalez, P. J., Bresciani, J. &amp; Conradi, M. (2006) New genus, three new species and new records of Herpyllobiidae Hansen, 1892 (Crustacea, Copepoda), parasites of polychaetes from Antarctica. Scientia Marina, 70, 243 - 259. https: // doi. org / 10.3989 / scimar. 2006.70 n 2243." type="journal article" year="2006">
López-González 
<emphasis box="[343,399,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">et al.</emphasis>
(2006)
</bibRefCitation>
, and males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="M. Sars" authorityYear="1870" box="[644,793,223,248]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Herpyllobiidae" genus="Eurysilenium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[644,793,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Eurysilenium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which possess a pair of stylet-like structures of uncertain affinity in the oral region (
<bibRefCitation author="Lutzen, J." box="[448,602,260,285]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="241 - 274" refId="ref47649" refString="Lutzen, J. (1964 a) A revision of the family Herpyllobiidae, (parasitic copepods) with notes on hosts and distribution. Ophelia, 1, 241 - 274. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00785326.1964.10416282" type="journal article" year="1964">Lützen 1964a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
